<paragraph blockId="158.[93,2535,3235,3484]" box="[95,1221,3462,3483]" pageId="158" pageNumber="761">
Mozambique Thicket Rat (
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Thomas &amp; Wroughton" baseAuthorityYear="1908" box="[379,623,3462,3483]" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Grammomys" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="158" pageNumber="761" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="cometes">Grammomys cometes</taxonomicName>
); 468. Woodland Thicket Rat (
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Smuts" baseAuthorityYear="1832" box="[950,1211,3462,3483]" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Grammomys" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="158" pageNumber="761" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="dolichurus">Grammomys dolichurus</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="159.[781,1375,303,723]" pageId="159" pageNumber="762">
shaggy, long-haired, and reddish-brown in color dorsally and dull gray ventrally. Head is broad, with short muzzle, vibrissae long, and ears rounded and well furred on inside. Tail is relatively shorter (70% of head-body length) than that of any other 
<taxonomicName box="[781,890,532,566]" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Dasymys" higherTaxonomySource="CoL,GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="159" pageNumber="762" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Dasymys</taxonomicName>
, uniformly black, heavily scaled, and sparsely haired.
</paragraph>
